description: From Middle English produce, from Latin prōdūcō (“to lead forth”), from prō- (“forth, forward”) + dūcō (“to lead, bring”). The noun is derived from the verb.

entries.meaning: Harvested agricultural goods collectively, especially vegetables and fruit, but possibly including eggs, dairy products and meat; the saleable food products of farms.

examples: With regard to the mare that has proved herself of the first class during her racing career, let us contrast the probable success of her produce  […]

verbs.description: produce (third-person singular simple present produces, present participle producing, simple past and past participle produced)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To bring forth, to yield, make, manufacture, or otherwise generate.

examples: Now it is also my understanding, I believe I am correct in this, that either one or two other manufacturers did not produce this year, which also created a certain shortage.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To make (a thing) available to a person, an authority, etc.; to provide for inspection.
(transitive, media) To sponsor and present (a motion picture, etc) to an audience or to the public.
(mathematics) To extend an area, or lengthen a line.
examples: to produce a side of a triangle

entries.meaning: (obsolete) To draw out; to extend; to lengthen or prolong.
(music) To alter using technology, as opposed to simply performing.
